export const sections: SectionHtml[] = [
 { "anchor": "opener", "html": "<p>The brief behind this paper says hard materials resist simulation <em>and</em> identification. Chapters 4–12 prosecuted the simulate axis; this chapter owns the identify axis. My claim is direct: stability and synthesizability are the under-priced axis of computational materials. Performance descriptors are a crowded trade — their errors benchmarked, their leaderboards public — while predicting what can be <em>made and kept</em> is where the field is thinnest and buyers pay most. Five parables first; the generalization after.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s14-1", "html": "<p>The crowded axis is real and well measured: adsorption energies carry a twice-documented ±0.2 eV floor (Chapter 8), and perovskite gaps agree with experiment only through error cancellations that fail outside their home composition (Chapter 12). Then, in December 2025, the field's own meta-analysis said the quiet part out loud — Chatterjee and co-workers showed that overpotential screening at realistic DFT uncertainty &quot;misclassif[ies] a broad fraction of the datasets as 'good'&quot; (a single-study result I treat as indicative, not settled; Chapter 8 carries the full statement), and called for a shift &quot;towards other metrics such as synthesizability, stability, lifetime or affordability.&quot;<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"44\">[44]</sup> I read that paper as the identify-axis concession speech: when the optimized descriptor cannot rank winners at achievable accuracy, the binding constraint moves to whether the candidate can be made — and whether it survives its job.</p>\n<p>The buyer evidence rhymes. Kemira's PFAS-capture brief to CuspAI demanded chemistry that is &quot;water-stable, environmentally compatible, synthesizable, and cost-effective&quot; — three of four constraints identify-class — and the paid deliverable was a narrowed, property-annotated candidate set on a six-month deadline, not a leaderboard rank.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"240\">[240]</sup> Section 3.5 staked the thesis; the five cases below are its evidence base.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s14-2", "html": "<p>Table 14.1 maps the five; the paragraphs give each its numbers and its moral.</p>\n<p><strong>Table 14.1 — Five stability parables: what screening predicted, what happened.</strong></p>\n<div class=\"tablewrap\"><table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>Case</th>\n<th>Failure timescale / energy</th>\n<th>What screening predicted</th>\n<th>What happened</th>\n<th>Source</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>MOF-74-class frameworks</td>\n<td>Hydrolysis driving force 200–250 kJ/mol per metal; room-temperature persistence masks fate</td>\n<td>Uptake-ranked champions; ML water-stability classifiers at 83%/71% accuracy</td>\n<td>&gt;100,000 structures → a handful of products; classifier accuracy collapses under grouped splits</td>\n<td><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"45\">[45]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"338\">[338]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"339\">[339]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"341\">[341]</sup></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Ti<span class=\"math\">$_3$</span>C<span class=\"math\">$_2$</span>T<span class=\"math\">$_x$</span> MXene</td>\n<td>42/85/100% degraded at 5/10/15 days in open water; ~30 days to anatase + carbon</td>\n<td>~320 mAh/g Li capacity (bare-flake DFT), ~2× experiment</td>\n<td>Days-scale oxidation; shelf-life engineering substitutes for intrinsic stability</td>\n<td><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"111\">[111]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"375\">[375]</sup></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Halide-perovskite PV</td>\n<td>Warranty-limited: 10-yr product / 20-yr power vs silicon's 25–30 yr</td>\n<td>Certified tandems to 35.5% efficiency</td>\n<td>~0.3% of manufacturing capacity; record-holder has no mass-production plan; durability bar is a 45-day outdoor test</td>\n<td><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"345\">[345]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"346\">[346]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"344\">[344]</sup></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>L1<span class=\"math\">$_0$</span> FeNi tetrataenite</td>\n<td>Ordering kinetics invisible to equilibrium thermodynamics; meteorites needed geological time</td>\n<td>A plausible mid-tier magnet, ranked and parked</td>\n<td>Phosphorus-assisted casting orders it &quot;within seconds&quot; (2022); no volume producer as of 2026-07-17</td>\n<td><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"267\">[267]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"268\">[268]</sup></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Operando catalysts (Cu)</td>\n<td>Reconstruction under bias; OC20 labels corrupted, MAE −35% when excluded</td>\n<td>Static-slab rankings of idealized surfaces</td>\n<td>The working catalyst forms in situ — nanograins, not the screened slab</td>\n<td><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"228\">[228]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"3\">[3]</sup></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s14-2-1", "html": "<p>The MOF parable names the doctrine. Calorimetry places the MOF-74 family's hydrolysis driving force 200–250 kJ/mol per metal center (<span class=\"math\">$\\approx 2.1$</span>–<span class=\"math\">$2.6$</span> eV; 96.485 kJ/mol = 1 eV) beyond that of ZIFs, and the authors do not hedge: &quot;these MOFs will eventually undergo hydrolysis,&quot; slowly at room temperature, faster when heated.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"45\">[45]</sup> One market analysis counts more than 100,000 synthesized MOFs against a handful of commercial products.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"338\">[338]</sup> The ML response has been honest but insufficient: first-generation water-stability classifiers reached 83% (two-class) and 71% (three-class) accuracy;<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"339\">[339]</sup> a fourfold data enlargement bought ROC-AUC above 0.8;<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"340\">[340]</sup> an independent re-benchmark then showed accuracy collapsing under metal- and topology-grouped splits — an &quot;optimism gap&quot; partly fed by duplicate structures.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"341\">[341]</sup> Chapter 11 gives the dispersion-side story; the identify-side story is that labels record kinetic persistence and thermodynamics does not care.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s14-2-2", "html": "<p>The 2D analogue runs on a faster clock. Ti<span class=\"math\">$_3$</span>C<span class=\"math\">$_2$</span>T<span class=\"math\">$_x$</span> dispersions degrade about 42%, 85%, and 100% after 5, 10, and 15 days in an open vial — water, not just oxygen, is the primary driver — and decompose fully to anatase and disordered carbon within ~30 days in air.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"111\">[111]</sup> Against that clock, idealized bare-flake DFT promises ~320 mAh/g of lithium storage, roughly twice what real, terminated flakes deliver.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"375\">[375]</sup> Screening optimized the headline property of a structure with a two-week shelf life; Chapter 11 carries the termination-error ledger.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s14-2-3", "html": "<p>Perovskite photovoltaics hold certified tandem records to 35.5% (announced July 2026),<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"344\">[344]</sup> yet commercial trackers list the flagship vendor at a 10-year product and 20-year power warranty against silicon's 25–30-year standard, with ~1.5 GW of manufacturing capacity against &gt;540 GW of annual installations — about 0.3%.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"345\">[345]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"346\">[346]</sup> The outdoor durability proof point is a 45-day Dubai field test, and record-holder LONGi states it has no active mass-production plan, citing long-term stability among the open problems.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"345\">[345]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"346\">[346]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"344\">[344]</sup> Chapter 12 documents the error-cancelled gap predictions; the market gate is metastable lifetime under moisture, heat, and ion migration — none of it represented in efficiency screening.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s14-2-4", "html": "<p>L1<span class=\"math\">$_0$</span>-ordered FeNi was computationally respectable for decades; equilibrium screening ranked it a plausible mid-tier magnet and stopped there. Its formation is restricted by &quot;a low atomic ordering temperature and consequently sluggish kinetics,&quot; so the bulk samples nature made arrived in meteorites cooled over millions of years.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"267\">[267]</sup> The blocker was kinetic, invisible to every equilibrium method in the funnel. The 2022 unlock was process chemistry: meteorites carry phosphorus, phosphorus accelerates Fe/Ni diffusion, and a Cambridge team cast hard-magnetic tetrataenite in bulk &quot;within seconds, without having to wait millions of years&quot; — yet as of 2026-07-17 there is still no volume producer.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"268\">[268]</sup> Chapter 9 tells the magnet-side story.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s14-2-5", "html": "<p>Under CO<span class=\"math\">$_2$</span>-reduction bias, copper surfaces restructure into in-situ-formed metallic nanograins that act as the active phase: the catalyst as-made and the catalyst at work are different materials.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"228\">[228]</sup> Reconstruction already contaminates the flagship corpus: OC20 systems that reconstruct break the adsorption-energy referencing scheme; one study finds that excluding them from validation cuts energy MAE ~35%.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"3\">[3]</sup> Chapter 8 gives the full ledger, including single-atom catalysts coarsening into 2-nm particles. The identify-axis point stands alone: an activity screen ranks structures that cease to exist at operating potential — stability is not a filter after the ranking; it determines what the ranking was about.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s14-2-6", "html": "<p>Each failure was, in retrospect, unsurprising physics: hydrolysis, oxidation, reconstruction, ordering kinetics, polymorph competition. What differs is the clock — days for MXene, years for perovskite warranties, geological time for tetrataenite, time-to-bias for catalysts — and the adversary: usually water, oxygen, the material's own operating conditions, or the phase diagram's other minima. None was in the objective function. The identify axis is not harder science; it is unrouted science, sitting in calorimetry papers and warranty tables while the field tuned descriptors. The data exist, the screens are cheap, and almost nobody runs them first — which is why I call the axis under-priced.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s14-3", "html": "<p>My doctrine attaches a stability dossier, five screens deep, to every shipped candidate before a single performance number is quoted. First, a <strong>hydrolysis screen</strong>: thermodynamic driving force toward hydrolyzed products, calorimetry-anchored where data exist; room-temperature persistence is not stability, and 200 kJ/mol of driving force finds its kinetic path eventually.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"45\">[45]</sup> Second, an <strong>oxidation screen</strong>: days-scale degradation in air and water on the MXene clock; a candidate that needs cryogenic storage is a logistics product, not a materials product.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"111\">[111]</sup> Third, an <strong>operando-reconstruction screen</strong>: will the candidate survive its own working conditions of bias, coverage, and potential? If the active phase forms in situ, the screened structure is a precursor and must be labeled one.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"228\">[228]</sup> Fourth, an <strong>ordering-kinetics screen</strong>: equilibrium stability is necessary, not sufficient; the dossier asks for a diffusion path at accessible temperature and time, the question tetrataenite's meteorites answered and its screening funnel never did.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"267\">[267]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"268\">[268]</sup> Fifth, a <strong>competing-polymorph screen</strong>: what else does the phase diagram want to be? Two of the field's most-cited materials chemists found &quot;scant evidence&quot; for compounds meeting the novelty–credibility–utility trifecta among GNoME's 2.2 million crystals,<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"30\">[30]</sup> and a peer re-analysis of the flagship autonomous-lab claim concluded its novel compounds did not survive characterization scrutiny.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"29\">[29]</sup> &quot;Stable on the hull&quot; is not &quot;makeable in a furnace.&quot;</p>\n<p>I will put my own position in one sentence, because I want it quoted back to me: <strong>I would rather ship ten candidates that survive water than ten thousand that maximize uptake.</strong> Uptake is a simulation output; survival is a deliverable.</p>\n<p>The dossier also compounds. Every screened candidate, pass or fail, becomes labeled data for the very stability classifiers whose optimism gap §14.2.1 documents — closing a loop that literature-label training could not close, because the new labels come from screens, not survivorship-biased papers.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"340\">[340]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"341\">[341]</sup> That loop is discovery chain 10, which Chapter 15 writes in full: stability-first screening coupled to autonomous-lab validation, yielding validated, makeable candidates at scale — and with them the one asset this field is shortest on. Not predictions. Trust.</p>\n" },
]
